definition.value: A growth phenotype which describes the resistance of individuals or populations after exposure to dimethomorph. Typically, organisms are deemed resistant to a chemical if they survive at a concentration of the chemical that does not allow wild type individuals or populations to grow.

A growth phenotype which describes the sensitivity of individuals or populations after exposure to dimethomorph. Typically, organisms are deemed sensitive to a chemical if they stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of the chemical that allows wild type individuals or populations to grow.
A growth phenotype which describes the absence of change of individuals or populations after exposure to dimethomorph (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: A single species phenotype where the frequency of occurrence of nuclei within an asexual spore is increased.

value.value: An amino acid chain that is produced de novo by ribosome-mediated translation of a genetically-encoded mRNA, and any derivatives thereof.

definition.value: The definition above excludes protein complexes, which some also consider a protein. Those who wish to refer to a class representing both senses of the word are directed to CHEBI:36080. Note that the definition allows for experimentally-manipulated genes, and allows for artifically-produced derivatives that mimic those found naturally. Proteins (in the sense defined here) that descended from a common ancestor can be classified into families and superfamilies composed of products of evolutionarily-related genes. The domain architecture of a protein is described by the order of its constituent domains. Proteins with the same domains in the same order are defined as homeomorphic [PRO:WCB].

value.value: An organic amino compound that consists of amino acid residues (unmodified amino-acid residues and/or modified amino-acid residues) linked by peptide bonds or derivatives of such bonds.

definition.value: Category=polymer.

value.value: A protein that is encoded in the genome of some Eukaryota.
A material entity that minimally consists of a protein.

definition.value: Note: This includes single proteins and derivatives thereof (PR:000000001), protein-containing complexes (GO:0032991), and protein aggregates (PR:000050566).

value.value: Material anatomical entity that is a single connected structure with inherent 3D shape generated by coordinated expression of the organism's own genome.
The stage of development at which the animal is fully formed, including immaturity and maturity. Includes both sexually immature stage, and adult stage.
A life cycle stage that starts with fertilization and ends with the fully formed embryo.
End of the life of an organism.
Stage succeeding embryo, including mature structure.
An entire span of an organism's life. In metazoans, commences with the zygote stage and ends with the death of the organism.
A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
A stage at which the organism is a single cell produced by means of sexual reproduction.
A stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
